    <div class="intro-section">
        <p>Now that you understand what databases are and how they work, it's time to learn about <strong>database relationships</strong>. In modern software development, it's crucial to understand how different pieces of data connect to each other.</p>
        
        <p>Think of it this way: In a school system, students are connected to courses, teachers are connected to students, and grades are connected to both. These connections are called <strong>relationships</strong>.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">What Are Database Relationships?</h2>
    
    <div class="explanation-section">
        <p>In a relational database, relationships between tables define how data is connected. Understanding these relationships helps you structure your database in a logical and efficient way.</p>
        
        <p><strong>Simple analogy:</strong> Think of a family tree:</p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>One parent</strong> can have <strong>many children</strong> (One-to-Many)</li>
            <li><strong>One person</strong> has <strong>one birth certificate</strong> (One-to-One)</li>
            <li><strong>Students</strong> can attend <strong>many courses</strong>, and <strong>courses</strong> can have <strong>many students</strong> (Many-to-Many)</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">Why Are Database Relationships Important?</h2>
    
    <div class="importance-section">
        <p>In real-world applications, data is rarely stored in a single table. Instead, it's organized into multiple tables that connect to each other. Here's why relationships matter:</p>
        
        <div class="importance-point">
            <h4>1. Prevents Data Duplication</h4>
            <p>Instead of repeating student information in every course they take, we store it once and connect it.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="importance-point">
            <h4>2. Keeps Data Organized</h4>
            <p>Related data stays together, making it easier to find and manage.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="importance-point">
            <h4>3. Makes Updates Easy</h4>
            <p>Change a student's name in one place, and it updates everywhere.</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="importance-point">
            <h4>4. Enforces Data Rules</h4>
            <p>Relationships help prevent errors, like enrolling a student in a non-existent course.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">The 3 Main Types of Relationships</h2>
    
    <div class="relationships-types">
        <div class="relationship-type">
            <h3>1. One-to-One Relationship</h3>
            <p><strong>Simple explanation:</strong> One thing connects to exactly one other thing.</p>
            <p><strong>Real-world example:</strong> A person has one passport, and that passport belongs to only one person.</p>
            <p><strong>Database example:</strong> User → UserProfile (each user has one profile, each profile belongs to one user)</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="relationship-type">
            <h3>2. One-to-Many Relationship</h3>
            <p><strong>Simple explanation:</strong> One thing connects to many other things.</p>
            <p><strong>Real-world example:</strong> A mother has many children, but each child has one mother.</p>
            <p><strong>Database example:</strong> Department → Employees (one department has many employees, each employee works in one department)</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="relationship-type">
            <h3>3. Many-to-Many Relationship</h3>
            <p><strong>Simple explanation:</strong> Many things connect to many other things.</p>
            <p><strong>Real-world example:</strong> Students and courses (students take many courses, courses have many students)</p>
            <p><strong>Database example:</strong> Students ↔ Courses (requires a special "join table" to connect them)</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">How C# Makes This Easy</h2>
    
    <div class="csharp-advantage-section">
        <p>The best part about learning database relationships with C# is that <strong>you don't need to write complex database code</strong>! Entity Framework Core (EF Core) handles the relationships for you.</p>
        
        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">Traditional Database Way (Not what you'll do!)</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
-- Complex SQL with JOINs
SELECT s.Name, c.CourseName 
FROM Students s
JOIN Enrollment e ON s.StudentID = e.StudentID
JOIN Courses c ON e.CourseID = c.CourseID
WHERE s.StudentID = 101;
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="code-container">
            <div class="code-header">C# Way with Entity Framework (What you'll actually write!)</div>
            <div class="code-content">
<pre>
// Simple C# code - EF Core handles the relationships!
var student = dbContext.Students
    .Include(s => s.Courses)  // Automatically loads related courses
    .First(s => s.Id == 101);

// Now you can access student.Name and student.Courses easily!
</pre>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        <p><strong>Notice the difference?</strong> With C#, you work with <strong>objects and properties</strong>, not complex SQL joins. Entity Framework does the hard work for you!</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-center">What You'll Learn in This Chapter</h2>
    
